[h1]Logical Operators[/h1]

Logical operators are used to join multiple expressions and return [b]true [/b]or [b]false[/b]. [img id="2456" width="100%"]
The [b]AND [/b]operator (&&) works the following way: [img id="2458" width="100%"]
For example, if you wish to display text to the screen only if [b]age [/b]is greater than 18 AND [b]money [/b]is greater than 100: [code format="cs" codeId="847"]int age = 42;
double money = 540;
if([b]age > 18 && money > 100[/b]) {
  Console.WriteLine("Welcome");
}[/code]
The AND operator was used to combine the two expressions.
[note]With the AND operator, both operands must be [b]true [/b]for the entire expression to be [b]true[/b].[/note]

[h1]AND[/h1]

You can join more than two conditions: [code format="cs" codeId="848"]int age = 42;
int grade = 75;
if(age > 16 [b]&& [/b]age < 80 [b]&&[/b] grade > 50) 
  Console.WriteLine("Hey there");[/code]
[note] The entire expression evaluates to [b]true [/b]only if all of the conditions are [b]true[/b].[/note]

