[h1]The OR Operator[/h1]

The [b]OR [/b]operator (||) returns [b]true [/b]if any one of its operands is [b]true[/b]. [img id="2859" width="100%"] 
[b]For Example: [/b][code format="cs" codeId="849"]int age = 18;
int score = 85;
if (age > 20 [b]|| [/b]score > 50) {
    Console.WriteLine("Welcome");
}[/code]
[note]You can join any number of logical [b]OR [/b]statements you want.
In addition, multiple [b]OR [/b]and [b]AND [/b]statements may be joined together.[/note]

[h1]Logical NOT[/h1]

The logical [b]NOT [/b](!) operator works with just a single operand, reversing its logical state. Thus, if a condition is [b]true[/b], the NOT operator makes it [b]false[/b], and vice versa. [img id="2860" width="100%"]
[code format="cs" codeId="850"]int age = 8;
if [b]( !(age >= 16) ) [/b]{
  Console.Write("Your age is less than 16");
}

// Outputs "Your age is less than 16"[/code]
